occurrences.line_text: To barre the prease of people farre away;
Through the thick prease, there thinking him to hyde.
The whiles the Prince hard preased in betweene,
Till that she rushing through the thickest preasse,
Into the thickest of that knightly preasse
Stood in the preasse close couered, well aduewed,
Forth from the thickest preasse of people came,
By whom they passing, through the thickest preasse,
There lay she couered with confused preasse
Vnto the caue gan preasse, nought hauing dout
But of all wisedome be thou precedent,
And promist to performe his precept well,
With precious mettall full, as they might hold,
Of perle and precious stone, that earthly tong
And precious odours fetcht from far away,
His precious horne, sought of his enimies
Laden from far with precious merchandize,
Yt framed was of precious yuory,
That all the ground with precious deaw bedight,
The vtmost rowme, abounding with all precious store.
Bearing that precious relicke in an arke
With pearle & precious stone, worth many a marke;
That precious iuell, which she formerly
Another Damzell, as a precious gemme,
To reaue her honor, which she more then life prefard.
Shall to that fairest Ladie be prefard.
Old loue is litle worth when new is more prefard.
And make his praise before his owne preferd:
When the full time prefixt by destiny,
And now he hath to her prefixt a day,
That in her pregnant flesh they shortly fructifide.
Into her pregnant bosome, forth she brought
And hearing th'answeres of his pregnant wit,
That nought mote hinder his quicke preiudize:
Made rowme, and passage for them did prepaire:
He started vp, and did him selfe prepaire,
And doest not vnto death thy selfe prepaire.
Thou recreant knight, and soone thy selfe prepaire
And vnto better fortune doth her selfe prepaire.
And vnto battell did her selfe prepaire.
And deckt with pearles, which th'Indian seas for her prepaire.
With humble seruice to her will prepard:
And fiercely vnto battell sterne themselues prepar'd.
Who soone prepard to field, his sword forth drew,
And all by wrong wayes for themselues prepard.
And to his purposd iourney him prepar'd:
But freshly as at first, prepard himselfe to fight.
The heauy plague, that for such leachours is prepard.
Vpon the plaine, the which himselfe prepar'd
He glad to satisfie, him selfe prepar'd
The Doune & eke the Frith, both which prepard her way.
As ready for the gallow tree prepard:
And to them way to make, with weapons well prepard.
The which themselues prepard thorough the foord to ride.
Vpon him ran; who being well prepard,
Them selues thereto preparde in order dew;
He burnt in fire, and gan eftsoones prepare
And seemely welcome for her did prepare:
Themselues of soiled armes, and to prepare
And gan themselues prepare to battell greedily.
He them espying, gan himselfe prepare,
And aye betweene the cups, she did prepare
And to the battell doth her selfe prepare:
Of his approch, and gan him selfe prepare
That might her loue prepare, and liking win theretoo.
But by one way, that passage did prepare.
Vppon some fowle, that should her feast prepare;
And as she did her selfe to strike prepare,
Himselfe vnto his iourney gan prepare,
And all his way before him still prepare.
And gan him selfe to fight on foote prepare.
Had left behind, he gan eftsoones prepare,
And him against his powre gan to prepare;
His bloudy vessels wash, and holy fire prepare.
Who whatsoeuer perill was prepared,
Talus desir'd, that he might haue prepared
But with his yron club preparing way,
But thou the same for pleasure didst prepayre.
And euer in your noble hart prepense,
But yours the waift by high prerogatiue.
Then seeke this path, that I to thee presage,
But if Sir Calidore could it presage,
That is the terme prescribed by the spell.
Then what prescribed were by lawes of cheualrie.
And to the Presence mount; whose glorious vew
Which with their presence faire, the place much beautifide.
Soone as the Elfing knight in presence came,
That greatest Princes presence might behold.
Whose presence I haue lackt too long a day;
Forth from her presence, by a narrow way,
At their first presence grew agrieued sore,
So fairely dight, when she in presence came,
Her ioyous presence and sweet company
By this his aged guide in presence came;
To her faire presence, and discrete behests.
In which her royall presence is introld;
Ne car'd he greatly for her presence vaine,
Least by her presence daunger mote befall.
When he in presence came, to Guyon first
Ne thou for better hope, if thou his presence stay.
By this that straunger knight in presence came,
But at these straungers presence euery one did hush.
Ne euer to her presence should presume,
Great comfort of her presence he conceiued,
Ne would they eate, till she in presence came.
She came in presence with right comely grace,
But as one daunted with her presence dread,
In presence came, desirous t'vnderstand
In presence of them all forth led her thence:
But here and there before his presence flew,
Whose presence all their troups so much encombred
Towards my Ladies presence by you ment,
Vnto the presence of that gratious Queene:
Those two strange knights were to her presence brought;
Admyr'd of all the rest in presence there,
From whose sterne presence they diffused ran,
Whereto when as my presence he did spy
To haue thy presence in my present quest,
At sight thereof, and from her presence flee:
That with her goodly presence all the rest much graced.
For present cause was none of dread her to dismay.
Ne yet of present perill be affraid;
To her makes present of his seruice seene:
They drawing nigh, vnto their God present
The which these reliques sad present vnto mine eie.
Present before the maiestie diuine,
That nothing may my present hope empare.
Would God thy selfe now present were in place,
That you, most noble Sir, had present beene,
The which good fortune doth to you present.
I present was, and can it witnesse well,
He oft finds present helpe, who does his griefe impart.
The present offer of faire victory.
Refuse such fruitlesse toile, and present pleasures chuse.
What flames (quoth he) when I thee present see,
But when as earthly wight they present saw,
Abide the fortune of thy present fate,
To teach them how to vse their present state.
The next could of things present best aduize;
And antique praises vnto present persons fit.
Vnto his Faerie Queene he might present:
Now were disarmd, and did them selues present
It was a famous Present for a Prince,
And of each shade, that did it selfe present;
He comming present, where the Monster vilde
I with me brought, and did to her present:
But those two sought nought, but the present pray,
But for the present did her anger shrowd;
That present were to testifie the case.
Since so good fortune doth to you present
The perilous present stownd, in which their liues were set.
That fayrest Florimell was present there in place.
That for this Ladie present in your vew,
That for the present they were reconcyld,
With which she for the present was appeased,
Where yet vntouched till this present day,
And to the present neede it wisely vsd.
Vnto this houre, this present lucklesse howre,
But there it present was, and did fraile sense entice.
And with him brought a present ioyfully
They saw it all, and present were in place;
Were present at this great solemnity:
So oft as I with state of present time,
Of present dayes, which are corrupted sore,
Seest not, how badly all things present bee,
That with this present treatise doth agree,
Which when as all that present were, beheld,
For sure he weend, that this his present guest
But that she saw there present in her sight,
She for a present to their Goddesse brought.
There present saw, each one of sence bereft,
And tempred for the time her present heauinesse.
Vnto the Souldans court, her to present
That brought her backe. And comming present there,
And many fearefull obiects to them to present.
To whom their sute they humbly did present,
The present of his paines, that Monsters spoyle,
Of which though present age doe plenteous seeme,
his state and present plight.
To haue thy presence in my present quest,
There he arriuing boldly, did present
He saw, the present mischiefe to redresse,
Both for the perill of the present stound,
Lo how good fortune doth to you present
Whom when the Hermite present saw in place,
So shall you soone repaire your present euill plight.
And with his teeth and nailes, in present vew,
Whose share, her guiltlesse bloud they would present,
And then to question of her present woe;
To finish then, for other present hast.
Where Calidore was present, he would loure,
Thy Loue is present there with thee in place,
Or to present her with their labours late;
Hither those Brigants brought their present pray,
And wishing oft, that he were present there,
She seemd, when she presented was to sight,
Eftsoones there was presented to her eye
Presented to the fayrest Florimell;
And hewing off his head, [he] it presented
Presenting him with all the rich array,
But presently was voide and wholly vaine:
But if that thou this Dame doe presently
Ne into ayre did vanish presently,
Whereof I haue to treat here presently.
That you into such perils presently doth call?
Yet since he was not presently in plight
As if they would haue slaine them presently.
Good lucke presents you with yond louely mayd,
Yet she no whit his presents did regard,
That this young Mayd, whom chance to her presents
First got with guile, and then preseru'd with dread,
Yet such, as were through former flight preseru'd,
Sith which it had bin here preseru'd in store,
I her preseru'd from perill and from feare,
But if few plants preseru'd through heauenly ayd,
Remaines on earth, preseru'd from yron rust
Thou canst preserue from wrong and robbery?
But to preserue inuiolated right,
And all that life preserued, did detest:
She was preserued from their traytrous traine.
If her Sir Artegall had not preserued,
Whereof no brauer president this day
And out of them to presse the milke: loue so much could.
And nought but pressed gras, where she had lyen,
They pressed forward, entraunce to haue made.
And as he pressed in, him there did slay:
He fiercely him pursu'd, and pressed sore,
From rudely pressing to the middle center;
And pressing through the preace vnto the gate,
The vengeance prest? Or who shall let me now,
And grudge, in so streight prison to be prest,
Vnwares haue prest: for either fatall end,
Who him affronting soone to fight was readie prest.
And after him Sir Paliumord forth prest,
In which his worke he had sixe seruants prest,
Loe hard behind his backe his foe was prest,
To warne her foe to battell soone be prest:
In stead of whom finding there ready prest
As they vpon him prest, it plaine to them did shew.
But as she prest on him with heauy sway,
He watcht in close awayt with weapons prest,
The whyles his saluage page, that wont be prest,
And from the citties to the townes him prest,
That further, then she willing was, he prest;
That did presume his fathers firie wayne,
Presume so high to stretch mine humble quill?
Ne euer to her presence should presume,
That beautie durst presume to violate,
His proud presumed force increased more,
As hagard hauke presuming to contend
For she presuming on th'appointed tyde,
Came ramping forth with proud presumpteous gate,
For the proud Souldan with presumpteous cheare,
Who came at length, with proud presumpteous gate,
And with presumpteous powre against that knight streight go'th.
A cruell Tyrant had presumpteouslie
And through presumption of his matchlesse might,
Where that proud Knight in his presumption
Thou that presum'st to weigh the world anew,
With flying speede, and seeming great pretence,
Which vnto things of valorous pretence
Or aerie spirit vnder false pretence,
Till that by dew degrees and long pretence,
To laugh at me, and fauour my pretence,
Without discouerie of my thoughts pretence,
For what their speares had fayld of their pretence.
That neuer entrance any durst pretend,
But would some rightfull cause pretend, though rightly nought.
She thought it best, for shadow to pretend
And perill by this saluage man pretended;
His target alwayes ouer her pretended;
Amongst the rest with boastfull vaine pretense
In glistring gold, and peerelesse pretious stone:
That shynd, like twinkling stars, with stons most pretious rare.
And in the midst thereof one pretious stone
With pretious bloud, which cruelly was spilt
Besmeard with pretious Balme, whose vertuous might
Those pretious hils from straungers enuious sight,
To trouble my still seate, and heapes of pretious pelfe.
And with great pearles and pretious stones embost,
So fell proud Marinell vpon the pretious shore.
Of pearles and pretious stones of great assay,
For gold, or perles, or pretious stones an howre,
Exceeding riches and all pretious things,
And all that else was pretious and deare,
Lapped in flowres and pretious spycery,
There was an Altar built of pretious stone,
Where beauties prize shold win that pretious spoyle:
This pretious ornament they say did make,
Eftsoones that pretious liquour forth he drew,
And thousand pretious gifts worth many a pound,
For neither pretious stone, nor durefull brasse,
But much more rare and pretious to esteeme,
Keeping there close with him in pretious store
Is ought on earth so pretious or deare,
And round about him many a pretty Page
On her two pretty handmaides did attend,
First doe the merry birds, thy prety pages
Her words preuaild: And then the learned leach
Who him gainstriuing, nought at all preuaild:
But when she saw her prayers nought preuaile,
Her prayers nought preuaile, his rage is more of might.
Tho when he saw no power might preuaile,
And by her deuilish arts thought to preuaile,
But when all this he nothing saw preuaile,
But when as all might nought with them preuaile,
But all in vaine, her plaints might not preuaile,
Might otherwise preuaile, or make him cease for ought.
Say, and do all, that may thereto preuaile;
Ne to recomfort her at all preuayld;
To giue him ground, (so much his force preuayled)
Th'ill to preuent, that life ensewen may.
Which to preuent, the Prince his mortall speare
With a strong gard, all reskew to preuent,
So th'euill thinkes by watching to preuent;
How to preuent the perill that mote rise,
But Cambels fate that fortune did preuent:
Which did not them preuent with vigilant foresight.
Preuented him before his stroke could light,
A thousand times him thankt, that had her death preuented.
Like shaft out of a bow preuenting speed.
The noble childe preuenting his desire,
He him preuenting, layes on earth along,
And from her griping pounce the greedy prey doth riue.
The day that first of Priame she was seene,
All three as one, the first hight Priamond,
Stout Priamond, but not so strong to strike,
And Priamond on foote had more delight,
But speare and curtaxe both vsd Priamond in field.
Gainst whom Sir Priamond with equall worth:
Right practicke was Sir Priamond in fight,
By Priamond, that with vnluckie glaunce,
By whose aduise old Priams cittie fell,
Who, after Greekes did Priams realme destroy,
Of Troian warres, and Priams Citie sackt,
Proud Priams towne. So wise is Nereus old,
For some shall pay the price of others guilt:
Shall with his owne bloud price that he hath spilt.
With thine owne bloud to price his bloud, here shed in sight.
Whose passing price vneath was to be told;
And captiues to redeeme with price of bras,
Ne would for price, or prayers once affoord,
With price of siluer shall his kingdome buy,
Ne worldly price cannot redeeme my deare,
Much more of price and of more gratious powre
Though vertue then were held in highest price,
They haue the price of their owne folly payd.
Adorned all with gemmes of endlesse price,
The more t'augment her price, through praise of comlinesse.
And sharpe Remorse his hart did pricke and nip,
Who seeing him from farre so fierce to pricke,
Gay steed with spurs did pricke, the good Sir Mortdant was.
To pricke of highest praise forth to aduance,
Then gan he freshly pricke his fomy steed,
Ne did he spare sometime to pricke himselfe,
The which like thornes did pricke his gealous hart,
Gan towards them to pricke with eger speede,
Ne feeles the thorns and thickets pricke her tender toes.
Her spightfull words did pricke, & wound the inner part.
Pricked with wrath and fiery fierce disdaine,
He pricked forth, his puissant force to proue,
They spide a knight, that towards pricked faire,
And pricked fiercely forward, where she him did vew.
He pricked forth in ayd of Satyran;
Priuily pricked with thy lustfull powres,
But yet he pricked ouer yonder plaine,
Eftsoones forth pricked proudly in his might,
Eftsoones they pricked forth with forward pryde,
When pride of youth forth pricked my desire,
So proudly pricketh on his courser strong,
A Gentle Knight was pricking on the plaine,
One pricking towards them with hastie heat,
Ere on the plaine fast pricking Guyon spide
His pricking armes, entrayld with roses red,
Then pricking him with his sharpe-pointed dart,
They spyde a knight faire pricking on the plaine,
They spide, where Paridell came pricking fast
He spide come pricking on with al his powre and might.
And Atin aie him pricks with spurs of shame & wrong.
His foe was nigh at hand. He prickt with pride
Him prickt, in pittie of my sad estate:
For on a day prickt forth with iollitie
And prickt with anguish of his sinnes so sore,
Till prickt with courage, and thy forces pryde,
Who prickt with courage kene, did cruell battell breath.
But prickt so fiers, that vnderneath his feete
Which them appeached, prickt with guilty shame,
His brother Morgan, prickt with proud disdaine,
His Beast he felly prickt on either syde,
The whiles the Prince prickt with reprochfull shame,
Till that prickt forth with loues extremitie,
So forth he fiercely prickt, that one him scarce could see.
Beheld, eftsoones it prickt his wanton mind
Fiercely forth prickt his steed as in disdaine,
By sundry meanes thereto she prickt him forth,
As when two Tygers prickt with hungers rage,
With speare in rest, and prickt with all his might:
And prickt him so, that he away it threw.
Whose loftie trees yclad with sommers pride,
With timely pride aboue the Aegyptian vale,
His foe was nigh at hand. He prickt with pride
As when two rams stird with ambitious pride,
Whose yeelded pride and proud submission,
He now Lord of the field, his pride to fill,
To sinfull house of Pride, Duessa
Ne Persia selfe, the nourse of pompous pride
That parentage, with pride so did she swell,
Their gay attire: each others greater pride does spight.
Drawne of faire Pecocks, that excell in pride,
Returnd to stately pallace of dame Pride;
Through wastfull Pride, and wanton Riotise,
Low vnder all, yet aboue all in pride,
Through wicked pride, and wasted wealthes decay.
Which all through that great Princesse pride did fall
The dreadfull spectacle of that sad house of Pride.
The house of Pride, and perils round about;
So oft as he through his owne foolish pride,
The plumes of pride, and wings of vanitie,
And rusht vpon him with outragious pride;
For th'antique world excesse and pride did hate;
All lilly white, withoutten spot, or pride,
By which she triumphes ouer ire and pride,
Peepes foorth, and soone renewes her natiue pride;
Who well could menage and subdew his pride,
Their blazing pride thou wouldest soone haue blent,
And after spent with pride and lauishnesse,
But later ages pride, like corn-fed steed,
And pompous pride eftsoones he did compound;
And with his pride all others powre deface:
His glory did enhaunce, and pompous pride display.
With all the ornaments of Floraes pride,
For soone comes age, that will her pride deflowre:
A dolefull heart with so disdainfull pride;
To that faire Mayd, the flowre of womens pride;
At hand with humble pride, and pleasing guile,
His threatfull pride, but did the more augment
That peerelesse paterne of Dame natures pride,
Withouten perill of the stronger pride:
Yet she it all did mar with cruelty and pride.
The Gate of good desert, whose goodly pride
Some of their pride, some paragons disdayning,
Nathlesse his pride full dearely he did pryse;
Old Cybele, arayd with pompous pride,
And if he shall through pride your doome vndo,
But he, whose spirit was with pride vpblowne,
Who with sterne countenance and indignant pride
Vntill that Talus had his pride represt,
But she them all despiseth for great pride.
The pride of Ladies, and the worth of knights,
And saw that boasters pride and gracelesse guile,
That all men wonder at her colours pride;
And for to maister wrong and puissant pride,
A Princesse of great powre, and greater pride,
Vnknowen perill of bold womens pride.
Like to an Eagle in his kingly pride,
Through vengeful wrath & sdeignfull pride half mad:
With an embrodered belt of mickell pride;
So great her pride, that she such basenesse much abhord.
That may pull downe the courage of his pride;
To fierce auengement of that womans pride,
And swolne with pride of his owne peerelesse powre,
Tho turning all his pride to humblesse meeke,
Then farewell fleshly force; I see thy pride is nought.
Then the reproch of pride and cruelnesse.
But he me first, through pride and puissance strong
The perill of his pride, or else be ouerrun.
Did worthily reuenge this maydens pride;
Euen for stubborne pride, which her restrayned.
Through her dispiteous pride, whilest loue lackt place,
So mighty blowes, or proue the puissaunce of his pride.
That pride doe not to tyranny you lift;
As if such pride the other could apall;
Which oft through pride do their owne perill weaue,
When pride of youth forth pricked my desire,
Of treble good: good growes of euils priefe.
For onely worthy you through prowes priefe
Of salues and med'cines, which had passing priefe,
Tell then, ï¿½ Lady tell, what fatall priefe
Me liefer were ten thousand deathes priefe,
Then searcht his secret wounds, and made a priefe
But the chaste damzell, that had neuer priefe
Till he had made of her some better priefe,
Consisted much in that aduentures priefe.
For all her paine, if please her make the priefe.
And with him brought Priene, rich arayd,
The Priest him selfe a garland doth compose
But them the Priest rebuking, did aduize
To whom the Priest with naked armes full net
And linnen stole after those Priestes guize,
Whereas the Priestes she found full busily
And spoild the Priests of their habiliments,
For all the Priests were damzels, in soft linnen dight.
Was hard to know, for that her Priests the same
Of many Priests, which duely did attend
For other beds the Priests there vsed none,
And on those Priests bestowed rich reward:
Of Bacchus Priests her owne deare flesh did teare.
Matched with equall yeares, do surely prieue
Ne would I it haue ween'd, had I not late it prieued.
In prime of youthly yeares, when corage hot
